extracted.value: Plaintiff: Jane Doe is a 21-year-old transgender woman who is entitled to receive healthcare benefits through the military’s TRICARE Health Plan (“TRICARE”), by virtue of being an eligible dependent of her father, Plaintiff John Doe.

patch.value: Plaintiff: John Doe, retired Senior Master Sergeant after more than 23 years of honorable service in both the Marine Corps and Air Force, who is the TRICARE Sponsor for Jane Doe.

evidence.text: Jane’s father, Plaintiff John Doe, retired from the U.S. military as a Senior Master Sergeant after more than 23 years of honorable service in both the Marine Corps and Air Force. As a benefit of his honorable service, John, his wife Susan Doe, and their only child (and dependent) Jane Doe receive healthcare through the Military Health System—specifically, through TRICARE. John Doe is considered the “TRICARE Sponsor” for Jane.
evidence.source_document: Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

patch.value: Defendant: Lloyd J. Austin, III, Secretary of Defense, sued in his official capacity, who oversees the administration of TRICARE and has authority over DoD policies.

evidence.text: Defendant Lloyd J. Austin, III is the Secretary of Defense to the United States and leads the Department of Defense (“DoD”). He is authorized to establish DoD policies, to include promulgating DoD Directives and Instructions that interpret and implement enacted federal law. Pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 702, Defendant Austin oversees the administration of TRICARE and, as such, he has a duty to ensure that TRICARE is administered properly in accordance with the Constitution and the laws of the United States. Defendant Austin maintains the ultimate authority, direction, and control over the DoD, including the TRICARE health benefits program. Defendant Austin is sued in his official capacity.
evidence.source_document: Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

patch.value: Defendant: U.S. Department of Defense, an agency of the United States government that manages military healthcare needs and oversees the military healthcare system.

evidence.text: Defendant DoD is an agency of the United States government. DoD manages the needs of servicemembers and their families and oversees the military healthcare system.
evidence.source_document: Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

patch.value: Defendant: Defense Health Agency (DHA), an executive agency within the DoD that manages and operates the TRICARE health program for over 9.6 million individuals.

evidence.text: Defendant Defense Health Agency (“DHA”) is an executive agency within the DoD and is funded through federal defense appropriations. DHA manages and operates the TRICARE health program, which provides worldwide medical, dental, and pharmacy programs to uniformed service members, retirees, and their families. On information and belief, more than 9.6 million individuals receive healthcare through TRICARE.
evidence.source_document: Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

patch.value: Defendant: TRICARE Health Plan, the healthcare program that covers Jane and John Doe, which manages and oversees an integrated healthcare delivery system under DHA authority.

evidence.text: Defendant TRICARE is the healthcare program that covers Jane and John Doe. TRICARE manages and oversees an integrated healthcare delivery system. Its director reports to and operates under the authority, direction, and control over the Director of the DHA.
evidence.source_document: Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief
